    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Because scale steps are not all equal, the intervallic patterns of chords formed by “every-other-note” stacking differ from chord to chord."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "C E G (4 + 3 semitones) is called a major chord, abbreviated “maj.” With C as the root, the full name is “C major” or “Cmaj.” It sounds open and stable."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "D F A (3 + 4 semitones) is a minor chord, abbreviated “min.” With D as the root, “D minor” or “Dmin.” It sounds softer."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Four-note stacks are called seventh chords because the span from the root"
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "note": true,
          "id": "dd30cbf1-cc2d-4700-8ac3-f4b8ce9efc22",
          "noteStr": "C4",
          "editing": false,
          "children": [
            {
              "text": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "to the top note"
        },
        {
          "type": "note",
          "note": true,
          "id": "e6e4a5a9-06a3-44cd-879e-095e0ea3de16",
          "noteStr": "B4",
          "editing": false,
          "children": [
            {
              "text": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "text": "is a seventh."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "We now meet the term “degree.” It’s simple: count the letter names. C-D is a 2nd, E-G a 3rd, etc. 1-3 is a major third (4 semitones), 2-4 a minor third (3 semitones). The nomenclature is historical; just memorise as needed (*^▽^*)."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Here is a table relating degrees to semitones—no need to memorise, just consult when necessary."
        }
      ]
    },
